@REMARK *                     Simulator Program                       *
@REMARK *-------------------------------------------------------------*
@NODE Simulator
@TOC "Instructions/MAIN"
@TITLE "Simulator Program"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The @{" Electrics Simulator " LINK Picture_Database/Simulator.0/MAIN} program simulates a project created by the
Schematic program.  Signal levels are applied, and the resulting output
levels are generated.

  @{" Window      " LINK Window} - Layout of program window.
  @{" Signals     " LINK Signals} - Signal levels and drive.
  @{" Scripts     " LINK Script} - Simulation scripts.
  @{" ARexx       " LINK ARexx} - ARexx support.
  @{" Limitations " LINK Limitations} - Limitations, bugs, etc. 
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *    Simulator Window          *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Window
@TOC Simulator
@TITLE "Simulator Program Window"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Information Box @{fg text}@{bg background}
        
At the top of the @{" program window " LINK Picture_Database/Simulator.1/MAIN} lies the Information Box.  This area
is used to indicate program status, and consists of the following 
three lines:

PROJECT: Project name.
SCRIPT:  Simulation script name.
MESSAGE: Error message or comment.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Simulation Controls @{fg text}@{bg background}

Under the Information Box are three buttons that are used to select
and run a simulation script.

"Script..." : Select an ARexx script.
"Run"       : Run the selected script.
"Stop"      : Stop the script or simulation.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *    Simulator Signals         *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Signals
@TOC Simulator
@TITLE "Signal Behavior"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Names @{fg text}@{bg background}

Signal names are the same names that were used to label Wires on the
original schematic sheet.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Levels @{fg text}@{bg background}

Four Signal levels are supported by the Simulator:
  
    @{u}NAME     LEVEL @{uu}
    Low        0
    High       1
    Unknown    X
    Floating   Z

These Signal levels may be applied to the circuit, or generated by the
circuit.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Drive Strength @{fg text}@{bg background}

Two signal drive strengths are supported by the Simulator; Strong, and
Weak.  A pullup (e.g. ELEMENT:PUP) is a Weak Signal driver.  This
means that a strong driver (eg. ELEMENT:BUF) can overdrive the Weak
Signal.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Contention @{fg text}@{bg background}

If two drivers with the same drive strength are connected together,
and each are trying to drive a Signal to opposite levels, contention
will result.  The resulting level on the Signal will the unknown "X"
level.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Initialization @{fg text}@{bg background}

When a new project has been loaded, or an existing one has been reset,
all Signals and contents of any memory elements will be initialized to
the unknown "X" level.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-------------------*
@REMARK * Simulation Script *
@REMARK *-------------------*
@NODE Script
@TOC Simulator
@TITLE "Simulation Script"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

A simulation script is an ARexx program that is used to initialize
all Electrics programs involved in the simulation, and then apply
Signal levels to the design.  All scripts are stored in the "Scripts"
sub-directory in the active Project Directory.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Script Selection @{fg text}@{bg background}

When the "Script..." button in the Simulator window is pressed, a
@{" Script requester " LINK Picture_Database/Simulator.2/MAIN} will appear with a list of available simulation
scripts.  Click on a script to select it, or press "Cancel" to not
continue.  When a script is selected, its name will appear on the
Information Box SCRIPT line.

The selected script is now ready to be run.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Running a Script @{fg text}@{bg background}

The "Run" button will pass the selected simulation script to the 
RexxMast program for running.  The Simulator then waits to receive and
process ARexx commands destined for it.  While the script is running,
the "Script..." and "Run" buttons will be ghosted (inactive).

@{fg background}@{bg text} Stopping a Script @{fg text}@{bg background}
        
The "Stop" button will stop a RUN command that is being processed, or
abort any ARexx command received while the button is pressed.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Result Message @{fg text}@{bg background}

When a simulation script has finished, the contents of the ARexx "RC"
return code variable are displayed on the Information Box MESSAGE line.
If "RC" is empty, then the "Script complete" message will be displayed
if there were no errors, or "Script error" if an error occurred.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Input/Output @{fg text}@{bg background}

A simulation script started from the Simulator will run quietly in the
background, meaning that any ARexx instructions used to print
messages or get keyboard input will have no effect.  If these
abilities are necessary, the script should be run in the ARexx Shell
program instead.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-------------------------*
@REMARK * Simulator ARexx Support *
@REMARK *-------------------------*
@NODE ARexx
@TOC Simulator
@TITLE "Simulator ARexx Support"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The Simulator program supports an ARexx interface for loading projects
to be simulated, managing Signals and Signal Buses, and applying or
examining Signal levels.

  @{" Message Port " LINK Port} - ARexx message port.
  @{" Commands     " LINK Commands} - ARexx commands.
  @{" Error Codes  " LINK Errors} - ARexx error codes.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *----------------------*
@REMARK * Simulator ARexx Port *
@REMARK *----------------------*
@NODE Port
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Simulator ARexx Message Port"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Port @{fg text}@{bg background}

Each instance of the Simulator program will have a unique ARexx port
name, beginning with the program name, and ending with the instance
number (e.g. SIMULATOR.1, SIMULATOR.2, etc.).  The last line of the
PROJECT menu ABOUT requester shows the ARexx port name for the program.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *--------------------------*
@REMARK * Simulator ARexx Commands *
@REMARK *--------------------------*
@NODE Commands
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Simulator ARexx Commands"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Commands @{fg text}@{bg background}

OPEN PROJECTNAME/A

  Loads all sheets of a project to be simulated.  Loading begins with
  sheet number 1, and continues contiguously until a gap is found in
  the sheet number sequence.
  
  If the project was loaded without any errors, the project name will
  be displayed on the Information Box PROJECT line.

  Example: OPEN COUNTER

CLEAR

  The current loaded project is cleared, including the Information Box
  PROJECT line.
  
RESET

  All Signals, including the contents of any memory elements, are reset
  to the unknown "X" level.
  
RUN TIME/N

  A simulation is run for a requested number of time units, or for
  one time unit if no time is given.  TIME may be as high as 4294967295
  time units.
  
  Examples: RUN
            RUN 5

CREATE SIGNAL/A,FROM/K,SIGNALLIST/M

  Creates a new Signal from existing ones in the project, or with
  ones that were also created.  Since the Schematic program does 
  not yet support Signal Buses, this command could be used to create
  one from individual Signals.  When creating a Signal Bus, the first
  Signal in SIGNALLIST is the most-significant bit.

  When a Signal is examined, the returned value will contain no more
  than 128 digits (binary, octal, or hexadecimal digits).  This sets
  a limit on the number of individual Signals that may be in a 
  Signal Bus.  
  
  Examples: CREATE MEMORY_IO FROM MIO#
            CREATE ADDRESS[3:0] FROM A3 A2 A1 A0
            CREATE ADDRESS[7:0] FROM A7 A6 A5 A4 ADDRESS[3:0]

REMOVE SIGNAL/A

  Removes a Signal from the Simulator, preventing it from being
  accessed.

RENAME OLDSIGNALNAME/A,TO/K,NEWSIGNALNAME/A

  Renames an existing Signal in the project, or one that was created.
  This command is useful for giving a Signal a name that is easier to
  understand.
  
  Examples: RENAME WR# TO READ_WRITE#
            RENAME D[31:0] TO DATA

ASSIGN SIGNAL/A,VALUE/A,BIN/S,OCT/S,HEX/S 

  Assigns a value to a Signal.  The Signal may be an existing one in
  the project, or a new one that was created.  A Binary value is
  assumed if no radix is given. Valid characters in the value depend
  on the selected radix:
  
  @{u}RADIX      VALUE CHARACTERS      BIT-WIDTH@{uu}
   BIN      0, 1, X, Z                   1
   OCT      0 to 9, X, Z                 3
   HEX      0 to 9, A to F, X, Z         4

  If the value bit-width is greater than the Signal bit-width, the
  extra higher bits in the value will be discarded.  If the opposite
  is true, the remaining higher bits of the Signal will be filled with
  a zero "0" level.
  
  Values can be assigned only to Signals that are not connected to a
  driver somewhere in the project. 
  
  Examples: ASSIGN CLOCK 0
            ASSIGN DATA 0Z001XX
            ASSIGN ADDRESS 8000 HEX

FORCE SIGNAL/A,VALUE/A,BIN/S,OCT/S,HEX/S

  This command is similar to ASSIGN, except that it can be used to 
  force a value onto a driven Signal.  The value will remain forced
  on the Signal until it is released, or assigned a value.  FORCE is
  very useful on tri-state or open-collector Signals that cannot be
  assigned a value.

RELEASE SIGNAL/F

  Releases a forced value on a Signal.  If no Signal is given, all
  Signals in the project are released.

  Examples: RELEASE
            RELEASE CLOCK

EXAMINE SIGNAL/A,BIN/S,OCT/S,HEX/S

  Returns the value of a Signal.  If a radix is not given, the returned
  value will be in binary.  A maximum of 128 value digits can be
  returned.  For example: only the low half of a 256-bit Signal will
  be returned as a binary value, but the full Signal value will be
  returned as hexadecimal, as it only requires 64 digits.
  
  Examples: EXAMINE CLOCK
            EXAMINE DATA[3:0] OCT

CONNECT REXXPORTNAME/A

  Informs the Simulator of the presence of an external program that is
  capable of responding to simulation results.  This command must be
  used after a project has been loaded into the Simulator, since the
  project's Signals are required while the connection is formed.
  
  Multiple instances of external programs may be attached to the
  Simulator (e.g. Three Digits and two Viewer programs).  REXXPORTNAME
  is the ARexx port name of the program to be connected.
  
  Example: CONNECT VIEWER.1
           CONNECT DIGITS.1
  
DISCONNECT REXXPORTNAME/A

  This command is the the opposite of CONNECT.  The Simulator will
  break the connection to the external program, and no longer
  communicate with it.

NOP

  This command does nothing.  It could be used for locating a certain
  instance of the Simulator program by sending the command to see
  if it is accepted, or if an error occurs instead.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------*
@REMARK * Simulator ARexx Errors *
@REMARK *------------------------*
@NODE Errors
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Simulator ARexx Error Codes"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Error Codes @{fg text}@{bg background}

0  = No Errors.
1  = Command aborted because Simulator was busy, or STOP was pressed.
10 = Signal name already exists and cannot be used again.
11 = Syntax error in command.
12 = Unknown command.
13 = Unable to find requested Signal name.
14 = Unable to find the ARexx port of a program to be connected.
20 = Out of memory.
21 = Unable to load project.
22 = Unable to find information for a schematic Symbol in the project.
23 = RexxMast program not running.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *------------------------------*
@REMARK *     Simulator Limitations    *
@REMARK *------------------------------*
@NODE Limitations
@TOC Simulator
@TITLE "Simulator Program Limitations"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

This version of the Simulator program has several limitations that
should be noted.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Zero-Delay Loop @{fg text}@{bg background}

A zero-delay loop will occur when the following conditions exist:

  - The output of a circut is fed back to the input.
  - The feedback path is inverting.
  - There are no delay elements in the feedback path (zero delay).
  - The feedback path is not at an unknown "X" level.

When the above conditions exist, the Simulator will appear to hang.
This is because such a circuit actually oscillates at an infinite
frequency and never becomes stable.  However, the simulation can be
stopped by pressing the "Stop" button.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Stopping a Simulation @{fg text}@{bg background}

A simulation can only be stopped if the Simulator is busy processing
a RUN command, or receiving any other commands.  If the simulation
script gets stuck while sending commands to a program other than
the Simulator, pressing "Stop" will have no effect.
@ENDNODE
